As, however, Colonel Stoffel (see p. xxxv) was an advocate of Gien, we must not ignore his reasons. He identified Vel- launodunum, from which Caesar marched in two days to Cenabum (11, §§ 1-5), with Toucy, which is 37 miles east of Gien3 and he insisted that this was just the distance which Caesar would have covered in two marches.
